### File Structure
```
OnlineAuction/
│
├── app.py
├── data/
│   ├── auctions.txt
│   ├── categories.txt
│   ├── bids.txt
│   ├── winners.txt
│   ├── bid_history.txt
│   ├── items.txt
│   └── trending.txt
│
├── static/
│   ├── css/
│   │   └── styles.css
│   ├── js/
│   │   └── scripts.js
│   └── images/
│       └── (auction item images like watch.jpg, iphone.jpg, etc.)
│
└── templates/
    ├── dashboard.html
    ├── auction_catalog.html
    ├── auction_details.html
    ├── place_bid.html
    ├── bid_history.html
    ├── auction_categories.html
    ├── winners.html
    ├── trending_auctions.html
    └── auction_status.html
```

### File Descriptions
- **app.py**  
  The main backend Python application file implementing the web server, routing, and all business logic. It handles reading and writing to the local text files in the `data/` directory, processes user requests, and renders the appropriate HTML templates with data. Since the application is not very complex, all backend logic is consolidated here.

- **data/**  
  Directory containing all the local text files used for data storage as specified in the requirements. These files store auctions, categories, bids, winners, bid history, items, and trending data in the defined pipe-separated format.

- **static/css/styles.css**  
  CSS file for styling the web pages, ensuring consistent and user-friendly UI design across all pages.

- **static/js/scripts.js**  
  JavaScript file for client-side interactivity such as button actions, filtering, sorting, and dynamic content updates without full page reloads.

- **static/images/**  
  Folder containing all auction item images referenced by the `image_url` field in auctions data.

- **templates/**  
  Folder containing HTML template files for each of the nine pages defined in the requirements. Each template corresponds to a page and includes the specified elements with their IDs for frontend rendering and interaction:
  - `dashboard.html` — Auction Dashboard page
  - `auction_catalog.html` — Auction Catalog page
  - `auction_details.html` — Auction Details page
  - `place_bid.html` — Place Bid page
  - `bid_history.html` — Bid History page
  - `auction_categories.html` — Auction Categories page
  - `winners.html` — Winners page
  - `trending_auctions.html` — Trending Auctions page
  - `auction_status.html` — Auction Status page

This structure cleanly separates backend logic, data storage, static assets, and HTML templates, facilitating maintainability and scalability while meeting all the specified requirements.
